calc-notation.name: calc
calc-notation.summary: The calc() CSS function lets you perform calculations when specifying CSS property values. It can be used anywhere a <length>, <frequency>, <angle>, <time>, <percentage>, <number>, or <integer> is allowed.
calc-notation.title: calc()

calc-notation.name: clamp
calc-notation.summary: The clamp() CSS function clamps a middle value within a range of values between a defined minimum bound and a maximum bound. The function takes three parameters: a minimum value, a preferred value, and a maximum allowed value.
calc-notation.title: clamp()

calc-notation.name: max
calc-notation.summary: The max() CSS function lets you set the largest (most positive) value from a list of comma-separated expressions as the value of a CSS property value. The max() function can be used anywhere a <length>, <frequency>, <angle>, <time>, <percentage>, <number>, or <integer> is allowed.
calc-notation.title: max()

calc-notation.name: min
calc-notation.summary: The min() CSS function lets you set the smallest (most negative) value from a list of comma-separated expressions as the value of a CSS property value. The min() function can be used anywhere a <length>, <frequency>, <angle>, <time>, <percentage>, <number>, or <integer> is allowed.
calc-notation.title: min()

urls.name: url
urls.summary: The url() CSS function is used to include a file. The parameter is an absolute URL, a relative URL, a blob URL, or a data URL. The url() function can be passed as a parameter of another CSS functions, like the attr() function. Depending on the property for which it is a value, the resource sought can be an image, font, or a stylesheet. The url() functional notation is the value for the <url> data type.
urls.title: url()

urls.name: url
urls.summary: The url() CSS function is used to include a file. The parameter is an absolute URL, a relative URL, a blob URL, or a data URL. The url() function can be passed as a parameter of another CSS functions, like the attr() function. Depending on the property for which it is a value, the resource sought can be an image, font, or a stylesheet. The url() functional notation is the value for the <url> data type.
urls.title: url()

lengths.name: length
lengths.summary: The <length> CSS data type represents a distance value. Lengths can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as width, height, margin, padding, border-width, font-size, and text-shadow.
lengths.title: <length>

lengths.name: length
lengths.summary: The <length> CSS data type represents a distance value. Lengths can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as width, height, margin, padding, border-width, font-size, and text-shadow.
lengths.title: <length>

sign-funcs.name: abs
sign-funcs.summary: The abs() CSS function returns the absolute value of the argument, as the same type as the input.
sign-funcs.title: abs()

sign-funcs.name: sign
sign-funcs.summary: The sign() CSS function contains one calculation, and returns -1 if the numeric value of the argument is negative, +1 if the numeric value of the argument is positive, 0⁺ if the numeric value of the argument is 0⁺, and 0⁻ if the numeric value of the argument is 0⁻.
sign-funcs.title: sign()

trig-funcs.name: acos
trig-funcs.summary: The acos() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the inverse cosine of a number between -1 and 1. The function contains a single calculation that returns the number of radians representing an <angle> between 0deg and 180deg.
trig-funcs.title: acos()

trig-funcs.name: asin
trig-funcs.summary: The asin() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the inverse sine of a number between -1 and 1. The function contains a single calculation that returns the number of radians representing an <angle> between -90deg and 90deg.
trig-funcs.title: asin()

trig-funcs.name: atan
trig-funcs.summary: The atan() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the inverse tangent of a number between -∞ and +∞. The function contains a single calculation that returns the number of radians representing an <angle> between -90deg and 90deg.
trig-funcs.title: atan()

trig-funcs.name: atan2
trig-funcs.summary: The atan2() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the inverse tangent of two values between -infinity and infinity. The function accepts two arguments and returns the number of radians representing an <angle> between -180deg and 180deg.
trig-funcs.title: atan2()

trig-funcs.name: cos
trig-funcs.summary: The cos() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the cosine of a number, which is a value between -1 and 1. The function contains a single calculation that must resolve to either a <number> or an <angle> by interpreting the result of the argument as radians. That is, cos(45deg), cos(0.125turn), and cos(3.14159 / 4) all represent the same value, approximately 0.707.
trig-funcs.title: cos()

trig-funcs.name: sin
trig-funcs.summary: The sin() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the sine of a number, which is a value between -1 and 1. The function contains a single calculation that must resolve to either a <number> or an <angle> by interpreting the result of the argument as radians. That is, sin(45deg), sin(0.125turn), and sin(3.14159 / 4) all represent the same value, approximately 0.707.
trig-funcs.title: sin()

trig-funcs.name: tan
trig-funcs.summary: The tan() CSS function is a trigonometric function that returns the tangent of a number, which is a value between −infinity and infinity. The function contains a single calculation that must resolve to either a <number> or an <angle> by interpreting the result of the argument as radians.
trig-funcs.title: tan()

mixed-percentages.name: angle-percentage
mixed-percentages.summary: The <angle-percentage> CSS data type represents a value that can be either a <angle> or a <percentage>.
mixed-percentages.title: <angle-percentage>

mixed-percentages.name: frequency-percentage
mixed-percentages.summary: The <frequency-percentage> CSS data type represents a value that can be either a <frequency> or a <percentage>. Frequency values, e.g. the pitch of a speaking voice, are not currently used in any CSS properties.
mixed-percentages.title: <frequency-percentage>

mixed-percentages.name: length-percentage
mixed-percentages.summary: The <length-percentage> CSS data type represents a value that can be either a <length> or a <percentage>.
mixed-percentages.title: <length-percentage>

mixed-percentages.name: time-percentage
mixed-percentages.summary: The <time-percentage> CSS data type represents a value that can be either a <time> or a <percentage>.
mixed-percentages.title: <time-percentage>

angles.name: angle
angles.summary: The <angle> CSS data type represents an angle value expressed in degrees, gradians, radians, or turns. It is used, for example, in <gradient>s and in some transform functions.
angles.title: <angle>

calc-constants.name: calc-constant
calc-constants.summary: The <calc-constant> CSS data type represents well-defined constants such as e and π. Rather than require authors to manually type out several digits of these mathematical constants or calculate them, a few of them are provided directly by CSS for convenience.
calc-constants.title: <calc-constant>

calc-func.name: calc
calc-func.summary: The calc() CSS function lets you perform calculations when specifying CSS property values. It can be used anywhere a <length>, <frequency>, <angle>, <time>, <percentage>, <number>, or <integer> is allowed.

notes: Before Firefox 59 calc() is not supported in rgb() and other color functions.
Before Firefox 57 calc(1*2*3) is not parsed successfully.
Firefox 57 increased the number of places calc() could substitute another value. See bug 1350857.

calc-func.title: calc()

dimensions.name: dimension
dimensions.summary: The <dimension> CSS data type represents a <number> with a unit attached to it, for example 10px.
dimensions.title: <dimension>

exponent-funcs.name: exp
exponent-funcs.summary: The exp() CSS function is an exponential function that takes an number as an argument and returns the mathematical constant e raised to the power of the given number.
exponent-funcs.title: exp()

exponent-funcs.name: hypot
exponent-funcs.summary: The hypot() CSS function is an exponential function that returns the square root of the sum of squares of its parameters.
exponent-funcs.title: hypot()

exponent-funcs.name: log
exponent-funcs.summary: The log() CSS function is an exponential function that returns the logarithm of a number.
exponent-funcs.title: log()

exponent-funcs.name: pow
exponent-funcs.summary: The pow() CSS function is an exponential function that returns the value of a base raised to the power of a number.
exponent-funcs.title: pow()

exponent-funcs.name: sqrt
exponent-funcs.summary: The sqrt() CSS function is an exponential function that returns the square root of a number.
exponent-funcs.title: sqrt()

frequency.name: frequency
frequency.summary: The <frequency> CSS data type represents a frequency dimension, such as the pitch of a speaking voice. It is not currently used in any CSS properties.
frequency.title: <frequency>

integers.name: integer
integers.summary: The <integer> CSS data type is a special type of <number> that represents a whole number, whether positive or negative. Integers can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as column-count, counter-increment, grid-column, grid-row, and z-index.
integers.title: <integer>

numbers.name: number
numbers.summary: The <number> CSS data type represents a number, being either an integer or a number with a fractional component.
numbers.title: <number>

percentages.name: percentage
percentages.summary: The <percentage> CSS data type represents a percentage value. It is often used to define a size as relative to an element's parent object. Numerous properties can use percentages, such as width, height, margin, padding, and font-size.
percentages.title: <percentage>

position.name: position
position.summary: The <position> (or <bg-position>) CSS data type denotes a two-dimensional coordinate used to set a location relative to an element box. It is used in the background-position and offset-anchor properties.
position.title: <position>

resolution.name: resolution
resolution.summary: The <resolution> CSS data type, used for describing resolutions in media queries, denotes the pixel density of an output device, i.e., its resolution.
resolution.title: <resolution>

strings.name: string
strings.summary: The <string> CSS data type represents a sequence of characters. Strings are used in numerous CSS properties, such as content, font-family, and quotes.
strings.title: <string>

time.name: time
time.summary: The <time> CSS data type represents a time value expressed in seconds or milliseconds. It is used in animation, transition, and related properties.
time.title: <time>
